Great! Let me compare **concrete class** vs **abstract class** in detail:

## Concrete Class

A **concrete class** is a regular, complete class that:
- ✅ **Can be instantiated** directly using `new`
- ✅ **Has implementations** for all its methods
- ✅ Can have both fields and methods
- ✅ Can be extended by other classes
- ✅ **Must provide actual working code** for everything it declares

### Example:
```java
// Concrete class - fully implemented
public class HashMap<K,V> implements Map<K,V> {
 private Node<K,V>[] table; // Instance variable
 private int size;

 // Constructor
 public HashMap() {
 table = new Node[16];
 size = 0;
 }

 // Concrete method - has actual implementation
 public V get(Object key) {
 int hash = hash(key);
 int index = hash & (table.length - 1);
 // ... actual code to find and return value
 return value;
 }

 // Concrete method - has actual implementation
 public V put(K key, V...meone needs to fill in the missing steps first

**Concrete Class** = Complete recipe with all steps
- "To make a cake: 1) Mix flour, eggs, sugar, 2) Pour into pan, 3) Bake at 350°F for 30 min"
- You can actually make a cake following this complete recipe

---

## In the Context of Dictionary vs Map

**Dictionary (Abstract Class):**
```java
public abstract class Dictionary<K,V> {
 abstract V get(Object key); // No implementation
 abstract V put(K key, V value); // No implementation
}

// ❌ Cannot do this
Dictionary<String, Integer> d = new Dictionary<>();
```

**Hashtable (Concrete Class that extends Dictionary):**
```java
public class Hashtable<K,V> extends Dictionary<K,V> {
 public V get(Object key) {
 // ACTUAL CODE HERE - complete implementation
 }

 public V put(K key, V value) {
 // ACTUAL CODE HERE - complete implementation
 }
}

// ✅ Can do this
Hashtable<String, Integer> h = new Hashtable<>();
```

