Excellent! Now let me compare **Abstract Class** vs **Interface** in detail:

## Abstract Class

```java
public abstract class Animal {
 // ✅ Can have instance variables (state)
 private String name;
 protected int age;

 // ✅ Can have constructors
 public Animal(String name, int age) {
 this.name = name;
 this.age = age;
 }

 // ✅ Can have concrete methods (with implementation)
 public String getName() {
 return name;
 }

 public void sleep() {
 System.out.println(name + " is sleeping");
 }

 // ✅ Can have abstract methods (without implementation)
 public abstract void makeSound();

 // ✅ Can have static methods
 public static void info() {
 System.out.println("Animals are living beings");
 }
}

// Usage: Must extend (single inheritance only)
class Dog extends Animal {
 public Dog(String name, int age) {
 super(name, age);
 }

 public void makeSound() {
 ...ete helper methods

 public abstract V get(Object key);
 public abstract V put(K key, V value);
}

// ❌ Problem: A class can only extend ONE class
class MyClass extends Dictionary { // Now can't extend anything else!
}
```

**Map (Interface):**
```java
public interface Map<K,V> {
 V get(Object key);
 V put(K key, V value);
 // ... more methods
}

// ✅ Advantage: Can implement multiple interfaces
class MyClass implements Map, Serializable, Cloneable {
 // Much more flexible!
}
```

---

## Summary Table

| Aspect | Abstract Class | Interface |
|--------|---------------|-----------|
| **What it represents** | Partial implementation | Pure contract |
| **State (variables)** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| **Constructors** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| **How many can you use** | 1 (single inheritance) | Many (multiple inheritance) |
| **Relationship** | "is-a" | "can-do" |
| **Example** | Dog **is-a** Animal | Dog **can** Run, Swim, Bark |

Does this comparison make the difference clear?

</agent_response>

