<agent_response>
Excellent question! Let me explain in detail why **interfaces cannot have instance variables**.

## What are Instance Variables?

**Instance variables** = Variables that belong to each **individual object** (each instance)

### Example with a Class:
```java
class Person {
 // Instance variables - each Person object has its own copy
 private String name;
 private int age;
}

Person p1 = new Person();
p1.name = "Alice";
p1.age = 25;

Person p2 = new Person();
p2.name = "Bob";
p2.age = 30;

// p1 and p2 have DIFFERENT values for name and age
// Each object has its OWN copy of these variables
```

---

## Why Interfaces CANNOT Have Instance Variables

### Reason 1: **Interfaces Cannot Be Instantiated**

```java
interface Flyable {
 // If this was allowed (but it's NOT):
 // int altitude; // ❌ ERROR!

 void fly();
}

// ❌ You CANNOT create an interface object
Flyable f = new Flyable(); // ERROR: Cannot instantiate interface

// If you can't create objects, where wo...lic void drive() { // Behavior
 speed = 60;
 }

 public void stop() { // Behavior
 speed = 0;
 }
}
```
- Defines **HOW** you do it
- Stores **data** (state) in instance variables
- Provides actual implementation

---

## Summary

| Feature | Instance Variables | Constants in Interface |
|---------|-------------------|----------------------|
| **Keyword** | No special keyword | `public static final` (implicit) |
| **Belongs to** | Each object (instance) | The interface itself (class-level) |
| **Can change?** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (final) |
| **Different per object?** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (shared) |
| **Needs object?** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No (static) |
| **Where allowed?** | Classes only | Interfaces and classes |
| **Example** | `private int age;` | `int MAX_SIZE = 100;` |

**Bottom line:** Interfaces define **behavior contracts**, not **state**. State (instance variables) belongs in the classes that implement the interface!

Does this detailed explanation make it clear now?

</agent_response>

